But this is only assuming that
after this presentation today,

00:29:50.770 --> 00:29:52.590
you go out there
and you start to use

00:29:52.590 --> 00:29:55.520
these types of techniques
to force yourself

00:29:55.520 --> 00:29:59.490
to commit more and more things
to memory and recall them.

00:29:59.490 --> 00:30:01.360
If you do that,
your memory is going

00:30:01.360 --> 00:30:03.810
to get better because the
brain is very trainable.

00:30:03.810 --> 00:30:05.470
Our brains are very trainable.

00:30:05.470 --> 00:30:09.570
The more you force your brain
to perform a particular function

00:30:09.570 --> 00:30:12.830
over and over again, the
more it signals to your brain

00:30:12.830 --> 00:30:15.590
that that's something important
for you to be able to do,

00:30:15.590 --> 00:30:18.300
so it will make itself
better at doing it.

00:30:18.300 --> 00:30:21.360
The opposite,
however, is also true.

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:24.614
If you never have your brain
perform a particular function,

00:30:24.614 --> 00:30:26.280
you're basically
signaling to your brain

00:30:26.280 --> 00:30:28.238
that that's something
not too important for you

00:30:28.238 --> 00:30:30.230
to be able to do,
so it makes sense

00:30:30.230 --> 00:30:33.520
that you will start to lose
that ability over time.

00:30:33.520 --> 00:30:37.360
We are all born with
extraordinary memory ability.

00:30:37.360 --> 00:30:40.480
We are born with our
brains like sponges.

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:43.880
We need this ability to
quickly acquire and learn

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:46.590
new information in order
to be able to survive.

00:30:46.590 --> 00:30:49.230
We reinforce throughout
all of our early years

00:30:49.230 --> 00:30:52.150
that learning and memory
is important by engaging

00:30:52.150 --> 00:30:54.570
in schooling, in preschool,
kindergarten, elementary

00:30:54.570 --> 00:30:56.910
school, junior high,
high school, college,

00:30:56.910 --> 00:30:58.240
grad school for some people.

00:30:58.240 --> 00:31:00.400
Throughout all of those
years you were constantly

00:31:00.400 --> 00:31:03.160
challenged to learn
tons of information

00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:04.820
from a wide variety of areas.

00:31:04.820 --> 00:31:07.910
You're constantly tested on
your recall of that information

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:10.550
for quizzes, exams,
to write papers.

00:31:10.550 --> 00:31:12.412
They say when you
first start a new job

00:31:12.412 --> 00:31:13.620
it's a lot of the same thing.

00:31:13.620 --> 00:31:16.050
You have to learn
a lot of new things

00:31:16.050 --> 00:31:18.520
and recall them in order
to do your job properly.

00:31:18.520 --> 00:31:21.005
But then what happens is
we tend to enter this 20,

00:31:21.005 --> 00:31:23.770
30+ year period where,
for the most part,

00:31:23.770 --> 00:31:26.830
you just start to do the same
things day in and day out.

00:31:26.830 --> 00:31:29.080
Everything just
becomes a routine.

00:31:29.080 --> 00:31:32.332
You are no longer nearly as
challenged to learn as much

00:31:32.332 --> 00:31:34.290
and recall as much as
you were earlier in life.

00:31:34.290 --> 00:31:37.770
The bottom line is we tend
to use our memory much less

00:31:37.770 --> 00:31:40.340
later in life than we
do earlier in life.

00:31:40.340 --> 00:31:42.690
So this is a large part of
the reason why your memory

00:31:42.690 --> 00:31:45.400
ability starts to
decline as you get older.

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:47.840
It's because as your aging,
you are separating yourself

00:31:47.840 --> 00:31:51.530
more and more from those early
years where you were constantly

00:31:51.530 --> 00:31:53.320
using your memory.

00:31:53.320 --> 00:31:56.220
The good aspect to this,
the positive aspect

00:31:56.220 --> 00:31:58.670
is that if you make it a
point to exercise your memory,

00:31:58.670 --> 00:32:01.880
actually use it,
it can stay strong

00:32:01.880 --> 00:32:05.410
and actually even get
better, really, at any age.

00:32:05.410 --> 00:32:08.280
Some people don't believe
me when I tell them this.

00:32:08.280 --> 00:32:11.720
They're stuck on this idea
that someone later in years

00:32:11.720 --> 00:32:15.650
is going to have a memory worse
than someone earlier in years.

00:32:15.650 --> 00:32:17.410
They think that's
just the way it is.

00:32:17.410 --> 00:32:20.880
So I like to talk about when
I competed in the World Memory

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:23.840
Championship, so I represented
the United States in the World

00:32:23.840 --> 00:32:26.780
Memory Championship in
the Middle East in 2008.

00:32:26.780 --> 00:32:30.090
I competed against
the guy-- when

00:32:30.090 --> 00:32:32.090
I represented the US--
I competed against a guy

00:32:32.090 --> 00:32:35.830
from Malaysia who, at the
time, was in his late 60s,

00:32:35.830 --> 00:32:38.100
so more than 30
years older than me.

00:32:38.100 --> 00:32:41.469
And he absolutely destroyed
me in the World Memory

00:32:41.469 --> 00:32:42.010
Championship.

00:32:42.010 --> 00:32:44.840
I was nowhere close to that guy.

00:32:44.840 --> 00:32:48.640
He actually memorized
an entire dictionary.

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:51.000
And they would call
out any page number

00:32:51.000 --> 00:32:53.855
in the dictionary
and the row number,

00:32:53.855 --> 00:32:55.980
and within a few seconds
he could tell you the word

00:32:55.980 --> 00:32:57.810
there and its definition.

00:32:57.810 --> 00:33:00.400
He can also do the reverse.

00:33:00.400 --> 00:33:02.435
If you said chair, he
would think about it

00:33:02.435 --> 00:33:03.810
for a few seconds,
say oh, chair.

00:33:03.810 --> 00:33:06.580
I think that's on
page 875, row three,

00:33:06.580 --> 00:33:08.400
and he was right
every single time.

00:33:08.400 --> 00:33:10.640
His name is Dr. Yip Swee Chooi.

00:33:10.640 --> 00:33:12.940
He's known as the
walking dictionary.

00:33:12.940 --> 00:33:15.500
He's from Malaysia.

00:33:15.500 --> 00:33:17.590
But it just goes to
show that really you

00:33:17.590 --> 00:33:23.260
can have a razor sharp memory
ability really at any age,

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:27.390
even after retirement age, 65,
usually the age people retire.

00:33:27.390 --> 00:33:29.580
You can still have
awesome memory ability,

00:33:29.580 --> 00:33:31.425
but he's always
working on his memory.

00:33:31.425 --> 00:33:33.680
He's constantly training it.

00:33:33.680 --> 00:33:37.090
That's why it stays very sharp.

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:38.010
So memory ability.

00:33:38.010 --> 00:33:40.220
One benefit.

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:43.180
You are also going to improve
your visualization ability

00:33:43.180 --> 00:33:44.950
with this type of training.

00:33:44.950 --> 00:33:46.430
You will notice
that you are going

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:48.600
to be able to create
these images in your mind

00:33:48.600 --> 00:33:50.450
much more quickly,
and you will be

00:33:50.450 --> 00:33:53.770
able to see the imagery in
your mind much more clearly.

00:33:53.770 --> 00:33:55.370
Visualization ability
has been linked

00:33:55.370 --> 00:33:56.790
to more than just memory.

00:33:56.790 --> 00:33:59.570
In fact, it's been linked
to overall intelligence.

00:33:59.570 --> 00:34:04.250
If you can visualize the complex
relationships between things,

00:34:04.250 --> 00:34:06.576
it helps to give you a
better understanding.

00:34:06.576 --> 00:34:07.950
Visualization
ability's something

00:34:07.950 --> 00:34:09.409
very important to develop.

00:34:09.409 --> 00:34:12.050
You will develop it with
this type of training.

00:34:12.050 --> 00:34:16.320
This is also great exercise
in creativity and imagination.

00:34:16.320 --> 00:34:20.360
Coming up with these creative
and imaginative stories.

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:24.355
In addition, this is a very
good workout for your brain.

00:34:24.355 --> 00:34:25.900
And all of the
research is showing

00:34:25.900 --> 00:34:28.570
that we should try to
exercise our brains as much as

00:34:28.570 --> 00:34:31.350
possible throughout
our lifetimes.

00:34:31.350 --> 00:34:33.190
The research is
showing that if you

00:34:33.190 --> 00:34:35.830
are destined to develop
Alzheimer's or another form

00:34:35.830 --> 00:34:38.110
of dementia down the road,
with current research

00:34:38.110 --> 00:34:40.969
they have no clue how to
prevent that from happening.

00:34:40.969 --> 00:34:44.860
But what they do believe is that
by engaging in rigorous brain

00:34:44.860 --> 00:34:46.870
exercise, you can
build up what they're

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:49.159
calling a cognitive reserve.

00:34:49.159 --> 00:34:50.949
So that's the
terminology that you

00:34:50.949 --> 00:34:53.356
would find in the research,
cognitive reserve.

00:34:53.356 --> 00:34:55.230
But basically, what this
means is building up

00:34:55.230 --> 00:34:56.960
extra brain muscle.

00:34:56.960 --> 00:34:59.490
And if you do develop
Alzheimer's, another form

00:34:59.490 --> 00:35:01.400
of dementia down the
road, the disease

00:35:01.400 --> 00:35:05.000
will first have to eat away
at that extra brain muscle

00:35:05.000 --> 00:35:07.080
before it starts to
affect your everyday life.

00:35:07.080 --> 00:35:08.455
So what they're
saying is you can

00:35:08.455 --> 00:35:10.210
gain more years
of mental clarity

00:35:10.210 --> 00:35:14.690
that you would not have had
otherwise without this reserve.

00:35:14.690 --> 00:35:19.460
So that's another benefit
of this type of training.

00:35:19.460 --> 00:35:24.150
In terms of applications, in
just a very short presentation

00:35:24.150 --> 00:35:27.010
like this, random words
is the easiest thing

00:35:27.010 --> 00:35:29.790
to go with because it just gives
you an idea of how this all

00:35:29.790 --> 00:35:31.700
works, and you get a
sense of how powerful

00:35:31.700 --> 00:35:33.320
these techniques really are.

00:35:33.320 --> 00:35:36.520
But I want to impress upon
you the fact that really,

00:35:36.520 --> 00:35:39.610
these memory techniques can be
applied to committing to memory

00:35:39.610 --> 00:35:41.720
anything at all that you
would want to remember.

00:35:41.720 --> 00:35:44.480
You can easily give a speech
or a presentation from memory

00:35:44.480 --> 00:35:46.070
without looking at notes.

00:35:46.070 --> 00:35:48.750
You can commit to memory
important business related

00:35:48.750 --> 00:35:50.140
facts and figures.

00:35:50.140 --> 00:35:51.790
If you can meet with
clients or get up

00:35:51.790 --> 00:35:54.860
in front of your colleagues
and give a presentation all

00:35:54.860 --> 00:35:58.360
from memory, with everything
at your mental fingertips,

00:35:58.360 --> 00:36:00.440
you are much more
impressive and you

00:36:00.440 --> 00:36:04.090
seem like much more of an
expert in your particular field,

00:36:04.090 --> 00:36:06.085
as opposed to
someone that's just

00:36:06.085 --> 00:36:07.710
reading the PowerPoints
the whole time,

00:36:07.710 --> 00:36:09.930
or just reading their
notes the whole time.

00:36:09.930 --> 00:36:12.390
In addition, the bottom
line is that we perceive

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:17.060
people with great memory ability
as being more intelligent.

00:36:17.060 --> 00:36:19.026
That's the perception.

00:36:19.026 --> 00:36:21.650
So you can help to give off that
perception with memory skills.

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:23.270
So that's another benefit.

00:36:23.270 --> 00:36:26.670
You can build up a vocabulary in
a foreign language very quickly

00:36:26.670 --> 00:36:29.610
and easily using these
types of memory techniques.

00:36:29.610 --> 00:36:32.300
Any type of exam that
involves a memorization

00:36:32.300 --> 00:36:35.590
of a lot of terminology,
concepts, you

00:36:35.590 --> 00:36:38.500
can easily ace
those types of exams

00:36:38.500 --> 00:36:40.470
with these memory techniques.

00:36:40.470 --> 00:36:42.510
There are really
limitless applications,

00:36:42.510 --> 00:36:44.430
but I'm going to close
my presentation today

00:36:44.430 --> 00:36:47.860
with my most popular topic
and that is remembering names

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:50.380
and faces, because this
is applicable, really,

00:36:50.380 --> 00:36:51.200
in any career.

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:54.110
Definitely applicable to
everyone's personal life.

00:36:54.110 --> 00:36:56.290
I like to quote the
famous book, "How

00:36:56.290 --> 00:36:57.910
To Win Friends and
Influence People."

00:36:57.910 --> 00:37:00.180
In that book it was written
that the sweetest sound

00:37:00.180 --> 00:37:03.550
to a person in any language is
the sound of their own name.

00:37:03.550 --> 00:37:07.540
And also, that everyone's
favorite subject is themself.

00:37:07.540 --> 00:37:11.500
So in fact, by remembering
people's names and other things

00:37:11.500 --> 00:37:13.490
about them, you can
build better business

00:37:13.490 --> 00:37:14.630
and personal relationships.

00:37:14.630 --> 00:37:17.150
The most important
thing of all to remember

00:37:17.150 --> 00:37:19.160
is the person's name.

00:37:19.160 --> 00:37:22.220
It's about building a
rapport with someone.

00:37:22.220 --> 00:37:24.380
If you meet someone at an
event and the next time

00:37:24.380 --> 00:37:26.670
you see him you can say
hey, John, how are you?

00:37:26.670 --> 00:37:28.120
How is your wife Nancy?

00:37:28.120 --> 00:37:29.830
How was your last round of golf?

00:37:29.830 --> 00:37:32.140
What that person
is feeling, even

00:37:32.140 --> 00:37:34.690
if it may be on a
subconscious level, is it

00:37:34.690 --> 00:37:36.190
they must be pretty
important to you

00:37:36.190 --> 00:37:38.820
if you can remember their name
and those things about them.

00:37:38.820 --> 00:37:43.090
And that, in turn, makes them
want to get to know you better.

00:37:43.090 --> 00:37:45.450
OK, so this strengthens
relationships.

00:37:45.450 --> 00:37:47.400
The most important
thing is the name.

00:37:47.400 --> 00:37:49.480
The opposite is also true.

00:37:49.480 --> 00:37:51.310
If you're not remembering
people's names,

00:37:51.310 --> 00:37:52.976
or maybe even worse,
you're calling them

00:37:52.976 --> 00:37:55.640
by the wrong name,
what they are feeling

00:37:55.640 --> 00:37:58.090
is that they must not be
very important to you,

00:37:58.090 --> 00:38:01.550
and this can be very
detrimental to business

00:38:01.550 --> 00:38:03.090
and personal relationships.

00:38:03.090 --> 00:38:05.620
So how do you get
better at doing this?

00:38:05.620 --> 00:38:06.830
Four simple steps.

00:38:06.830 --> 00:38:09.640
First, independent of memory
techniques, and then I'll

00:38:09.640 --> 00:38:12.170
get into a visual-based
memory technique after that.

00:38:12.170 --> 00:38:13.080
Step number one.

00:38:13.080 --> 00:38:16.140
From this day forward, get
into the habit, whenever

00:38:16.140 --> 00:38:19.150
you are introduced to
someone, make it a point

00:38:19.150 --> 00:38:22.860
to repeat the name right away
and shake the hand if you can.

00:38:22.860 --> 00:38:24.940
So if you're introduced
to someone named Jared,

00:38:24.940 --> 00:38:25.721
shake his hand.

00:38:25.721 --> 00:38:26.720
Nice to meet you, Jared.

00:38:26.720 --> 00:38:27.844
Pleased to meet you, Jared.

00:38:27.844 --> 00:38:29.080
Just get into that habit.

00:38:29.080 --> 00:38:31.967
That forces you to pay
attention for at least one

00:38:31.967 --> 00:38:34.550
to two seconds in order for you
to be able to repeat the name.

00:38:34.550 --> 00:38:36.761
A lot of times we're not
remembering people's names

00:38:36.761 --> 00:38:38.510
because when they're
giving us their name,

00:38:38.510 --> 00:38:41.220
we're just not paying any
attention to begin with.

00:38:41.220 --> 00:38:42.620
So get into that habit.

00:38:42.620 --> 00:38:44.880
Repeat the name, shake the hand.

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:47.530
Eventually it will just
become second nature to you.

00:38:47.530 --> 00:38:48.980
Step number two.

00:38:48.980 --> 00:38:51.700
Early on in your
interaction with the person,

00:38:51.700 --> 00:38:55.260
ask them a question
using their name.

00:38:55.260 --> 00:38:57.880
So Jared, how long have
you been with Google?

00:38:57.880 --> 00:39:00.800
Jared, how long have
you known Chester?

00:39:00.800 --> 00:39:02.850
How do you know Chester, Jared?

00:39:02.850 --> 00:39:05.539
Use the name early on in your
interaction with the person.

00:39:05.539 --> 00:39:07.080
That's really going
to help that name

00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:09.700
stick much better in
your mind and prevent it

00:39:09.700 --> 00:39:14.350
from just going in one
ear and out the other ear.

00:39:14.350 --> 00:39:15.990
Step number three.

00:39:15.990 --> 00:39:19.220
Take a few seconds
or less to think

00:39:19.220 --> 00:39:24.220
of a connection between the
name and anything at all

00:39:24.220 --> 00:39:25.150
that you already know.

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:26.360
And I would just go
with the first thing

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:27.401
that pops into your head.

00:39:27.401 --> 00:39:29.230
Today it was Jared from Subway.

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:31.340
I don't-- that's the
first one, sorry.

00:39:31.340 --> 00:39:33.590
That's the first thing that
popped into my head today.

00:39:33.590 --> 00:39:35.890
AUDIENCE: I used to use the
jewelry store, but that's OK.

00:39:35.890 --> 00:39:36.681
CHESTER SANTOS: OK.

00:39:36.681 --> 00:39:39.140
Whatever, just think
of a connection

00:39:39.140 --> 00:39:41.944
between the person's
name and anything at all

00:39:41.944 --> 00:39:42.860
that you already know.

00:39:42.860 --> 00:39:44.484
It could even actually
be that you just

00:39:44.484 --> 00:39:47.950
have a friend or family member
that also has that same name.

00:39:47.950 --> 00:39:52.150
It's really going to help you to
remember that name much better.

00:39:52.150 --> 00:39:53.330
Step number four.

00:39:53.330 --> 00:39:55.360
Whenever you leave the
party, the meeting,

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:57.340
whatever type of
function it may be,

00:39:57.340 --> 00:40:02.932
make it a point to say goodbye
to people using their name.

00:40:02.932 --> 00:40:05.140
Great meeting, hope to see
you again sometime, Jared.

00:40:05.140 --> 00:40:05.973
Something like that.

00:40:05.973 --> 00:40:09.060
That's going to go a long way
towards helping you to remember

00:40:09.060 --> 00:40:11.750
those names the next
time you see people.

00:40:11.750 --> 00:40:13.820
Those four steps alone
are going to help

00:40:13.820 --> 00:40:16.080
you a lot in terms
of remembering names.

00:40:16.080 --> 00:40:19.250
If you combine them with
a visual-based technique

00:40:19.250 --> 00:40:22.770
that I'll now briefly go
over, you will definitely

00:40:22.770 --> 00:40:25.670
be remembering more names
than you ever have before.

00:40:25.670 --> 00:40:27.050
You might not be 100%.

00:40:27.050 --> 00:40:28.820
Even I'm not 100%.

00:40:28.820 --> 00:40:32.580
But if you can remember 80+% of
the people that you're meeting,

00:40:32.580 --> 00:40:35.550
this is really going to pay
huge dividends in your career

00:40:35.550 --> 00:40:37.980
and in your personal life.

00:40:37.980 --> 00:40:39.280
Visual-based technique.

00:40:39.280 --> 00:40:42.340
When you are introduced
to someone, ask yourself,

00:40:42.340 --> 00:40:45.130
how does this person
in some way, any way,

00:40:45.130 --> 00:40:46.580
look unique to you?

00:40:46.580 --> 00:40:49.010
It could be a particular
facial feature

00:40:49.010 --> 00:40:51.530
or it could be something
about their look overall.

00:40:51.530 --> 00:40:54.680
And you want to exaggerate
that in your mind, whatever

00:40:54.680 --> 00:40:55.670
it may be.

00:40:55.670 --> 00:40:58.640
Next, you will use your
creativity and imagination

00:40:58.640 --> 00:41:00.570
to come up with an image
that will in some way

00:41:00.570 --> 00:41:05.160
remind you of the name, and you
will mentally link that image

00:41:05.160 --> 00:41:09.990
to the unique thing
about the person.

00:41:09.990 --> 00:41:12.360
A lot of times these might
not be flattering things--

00:41:12.360 --> 00:41:13.901
you're not going to
be telling people

00:41:13.901 --> 00:41:15.830
how you're remembering
their name, OK.

00:41:15.830 --> 00:41:18.260
This is all going on
inside of your head.

00:41:18.260 --> 00:41:19.490
They're not going to know
what you're thinking,

00:41:19.490 --> 00:41:20.330
they're just going
to know that you're

00:41:20.330 --> 00:41:22.760
able to call them by their
name and they will really

00:41:22.760 --> 00:41:24.760
appreciate that fact.

00:41:24.760 --> 00:41:28.492
I will quickly give you an
example of how this works.

00:41:28.492 --> 00:41:30.450
I will give you the
example that I gave on CNN.

